{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f6f02f72-fda3-4c6d-b79b-6023b338c04d","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2**, which supports the modern approach using **constructors** and `IAsyncInitialization` instead of the legacy `[TestInitialize]` / `[ClassInitialize]` attributes.\n\nHere's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting;\n\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncInitialization\n{\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; } // Injected automatically via constructor\n\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        // Synchronous init — runs first\n        TestContext = testContext;\n    }\n\n    public Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // Async init — runs after the constructor\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void SampleTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(TestContext);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`TestContext`** is injected via the constructor — no need for a settable property or `[TestInitialize]`.\n- **`IAsyncInitialization.InitializeAsync()`** runs after the constructor, giving you a proper async init phase (e.g., for setting up database connections).\n- This replaces the older `[TestInitialize]` + `[ClassInitialize]` pattern and avoids `async void` pitfalls.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5770b5ae-7bce-467a-b019-c17cdfa921ef","outputTokens":337,"requestId":"082D:144FCD:D4249F:F5AFF7:69EAC73F"},"id":"a57e7b79-605c-47fd-b2bd-0018e3f4fde9","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:28:39.414Z","parentId":"c6a2202e-2cf9-483e-9f6a-76c9198f8931"}
